A list of reported symbiotic siphonostomatoids from marine fishes of Southern Africa was compiled and published in 2004. At the time only 15 of the 40 families were reported which included only about 172 species (
Dippenaar 2004
). Thus, it is necessary to report on our progress regarding the knowledge about the diversity of the marine siphonostomatoids off Southern Africa about 20 years later and provide a more complete assessment of the current knowledge of the diversity of siphonostomatoids.

The list of reported siphonostomatoids of marine fishes off Southern Africa (
Dippenaar 2004
) is updated with records reported and changed since the publication of the list including previously omitted reports of siphonostomatoids collected from invertebrates and mammals (
Table 1
). Host names were verified using Fishbase (
Froese & Pauly 2023
) and Eschmeyer’s Catalog of Fishes (

Fricke 
et al
. 2023

), while siphonostomatoid names were verified with World Register of Marine Species (WoRMS 
Editorial Board 2024
). It is important to note that this report should be read in conjunction with the 2004 report (
Dippenaar 2004
) as this is not a repetition of the previous list since only changed and newly reported records are included.

The results are compiled into two tables. Firstly, a table (
Table 1
) with newly reported siphonostomotoids and new hosts and localities since 2004 as well as the relevant references. Included in this table are previous reports from 2004 with changes in their taxonomy.

Pandaridae (includes representatives previously part of Cecropidae (see Dippenaar 2004 )) (
Tang et al . 2012
) with the addition of four new species reports ( Table 1 ).

An update regarding the knowledge about the diversity of siphonostomatoids infecting marine organisms off Southern Africa is required since the last comprehensive report was published 20 years ago (in 2004) (Dippenaar 1994). The previous list only included siphonostomatoids infecting marine fish off Southern Africa. Apart from reports published since 2004 and species with changed taxonomy, unreported siphonostomatoids are also included in the current report. Therefore, the current knowledge regarding the biodiversity of Siphonostomatoida off Southern Africa includes 16 families, 75 genera and 234 species reported from vertebrates and invertebrates. New information about the state of our current knowledge as well as new host and geographic localities of the reported siphonostomatoids are provided. Furthermore, all records are combined in a single report (together with the 2004 report) with the latest references of additional reports since 2004 which will be very helpful to new researchers. Even though taxonomy is a living subject with “refutable scientific hypotheses” (
Raposo et al . 2017
) and changes in taxonomy can always be expected (especially in large families like Lernaeopodidae ), the current report will be a good starting point for anybody interesting in marine symbiotic siphonostomatoids off Southern Africa. Although there is an improvement in the reported biodiversity it is unfortunate that numbers are still very low compared with accepted numbers of species ( Walter & Boxshall 2024 ), especially considering the diversity of possible hosts (vertebrates and invertebrates) occurring off Southern Africa.

